metadata.name: sewn gate #46
metadata.description:
Now what?
Warmth and comfort?

The lines create carpet patterns with different patterns and angles each time. Squares, rhombuses, plain embroidery and many others.
Why carpets?

They are very attractive with their comfort. A house or apartment with carpets always seems more residential and warm, no matter what kind of carpet. One color or pattern doesn't matter. It performs not only a design or warming function, but also a pleasant one for the soul. I hope I was able to make your day comfortable!

metadata.name: contrapuntos #363
metadata.description:
Musical counterpoint is to me an abstraction of the layered, intertwining rhythms of every activity we carry on in our lives. With a global tempo typically set in days, we fit all sorts of temporal structures where our joys and fears live and play out over the span of our lives. This series is a metaphorical transposition of the musical counterpoint into a visual space, sometimes with repeating patterns, sometimes with broken structures, sometimes isolated notes / hours / souls.

Artwork by Marcelo Soria-Rodr√≠guez, @msoriaro. Made with p5js & glsl.

metadata.name: vapour trails #40
metadata.description:
‚Äúfirst you look so strong, then you fade away
the sun will blind my eyes, i‚Äôll love you anyway
thirsty for your smile, i watch you for a while
you are a vapour trail in a deep blue sky‚Äù

‚Äî Andy Bell (Ride) (1991)

this collection tries to capture that feeling of lying in the grass
in a park
staring at the sky
fantasizing about your love (if they even exist)
playing out different paths
while smoke from your cigarette (jazz or otherwise)
trails between you and the faraway of everything
feeling grateful to not have to be anywhere
but here (now)

with luck
they lay next to you
and silently you appreciate each tick of the clock
wasted together
until life again gets in the way
and pulls you back
into the fray

metadata.name: Miniscapes #121
metadata.description:
Miniscapes merges generative code (Rich's bit) with meticulously designed scenes and elements (Rick's bit), to create minimalist landscapes intended to charm, delight, and surprise.

Our aim was to convey as much as possible with as little as possible by using simple shapes and lines to represent a wide variety of natural landscapes.

We hope that you find as much joy in owning a Miniscape as we did in creating them.

Controls (in live view):
- Press [s] to save the current image
- Press [p] to pause an animated output
- Press [r] to reset an animated output (this will also pause)

metadata.name: Artifice #59
metadata.description:
This series is is about playful obfuscation.

The fxtext article linked on the main profect goes more in-depth into what is meant by that, as well as the events that led to this collection.

5640 bytes of Vanilla JS with no libraries. Palettes make up a third of the code.

In live mode:
‚ÄòS‚Äô : save as png (3000‚Ää√ó‚Ää3600)
‚ÄôV‚Äô : save as svg (without grain)

URL params in live mode:
‚Äòg=n‚Äô : no grain
‚Äòg=p‚Äô : paper grain
‚Äòh=t‚Äô : high resolution mode, 9000‚Ää√ó10600 (Chrome only, and may take a moment)

For example, if you wanted paper grain in high resolution, append ‚Äú&g=p&h=t‚Äù to the url in live mode.

After rendering with these params, tapping 'P' will then save a png with those settings applied.

metadata.name: Divisio(X) #69
metadata.description:
On a dynamic grid (2x2, 3x3, 4x4, 5x5 or 6x6), each cell is filled with one shape (out of 6). For each shape, a rotation (0¬∞, 90¬∞, 180¬∞, 270¬∞) and a stroke weight (from 5 to 100) are applied. A color palette (out of 6) and a number of layers (1 to 3) are applied to the canvas.

The background under the shape can be filled by cells, rows or columns. At times, a thick grid may also be visible.	

Generative abstract compositions. Coded in January 2022.

metadata.name: Swedish Forest #63
metadata.description:
If I had to choose a place where time was frozen and where I could contemplate the landscape for eternity this place would be a scandinavian forest.
I have been contemplating these kind of landscape for a very long time both in Sweden and in the Pyrenees where the ecosystem is very similar.
This project generates an illustration of a scandinavian forest in many different situations. At day and at night, in every season of the year, next to a lake or not, with steep hills or at the plains, snowing, with preponderance of some plant species over others, etc.
The artwork is also drawn in various paint modes and layouts.

The sun or the moon may be visible, the moon shows always the actual moon phase based on the current date.
The reflection on the lake is the fxhash morse endcoded.


Developed in vanilla js using svg and canvas
Rendering can be unresponsive on slow devices
Click or touch to switch to Parallax mode, just move the mouse or finger.


[S] Download in SVG format
[D] Download in PNG format

Features:

Layout: Landscape, Portrait, Square
PredominantSpecies: Blueberry, Lingonberry, Calluna, Rocks, None
Trees: Mixed, PinesAndFirs, Birches, None
Season: Spring, Summer, Fall, Winter
DayNight: Day, Night
PaintStyle: Normal, Stroke, Paint, WhiteOnBlack, BlackOnWhite
ColorStyle: Normal, Crazy
HasLake: True, False
HasTrees: None, Few, Many, Crowded

Created by Daniel Juli√† Lundgren, fxhash: danieljulia.tez, twitter: @daniel_julia. Licensed under CC BY-NC-SA 4.0, see LICENSE.txt for more information.

Generative abstract artwork that explores forms, shapes, coloring and brushwork.

Created using p5js.

@VolatileMoods, November, 2022.

metadata.name: VOYAGERS #108
metadata.description:
Generative animated painting made from looping gestures in a virtual void.

Voyagers is an exploration of automated gestures and screenspace layering effects. Each brush stroke sweeps through the canvas leaving a trail of color that either disappears or mixes with adjacent colors. The image slowly builds up to achieve an equilibrium between the rhythm of the gestures and the interaction of color values. These colors are quantized and dithered to produce chunky, textured, blocks of light that reify the materiality of the screen and the pixel. Two aspect ratios are possible, each with its own material relationship to screen-based work, 1:1 and 4:3 (vertical).

Press 's' to save looping animated GIF (live mode only).
Press 'p' to pause the animation.
Press 'c' to capture a single frame.
Made with P5.js and GLSL. By @galoandstuff.

metadata.name: New World #77
metadata.description:
A New World can form out of destruction or creation.

Inspiration: 
The forms that appear in New World evoke cliffs, islands, and other natural structures, but perspective distortions bend them into a surreal and new computational reality. 

The collection was in part influenced by my feelings during the first two weeks of the invasion of Ukraine. It was a time marked by anxiety, uncertainty, and disillusionment. But, New World was also inspired by the hope embodied in my creative process and the genart community. Hence, the collection takes on a double meaning: a new world can form out of destruction or creation. 

Algorithm:
The collection is completely generative and written with p5.js. It began as an exploration of the dual contouring algorithm and purposefully builds on a bug I introduced when filling the contours by selecting vertices out of winding order. 

Pricing:
Dutch Auction: 16xtz -> 12xtz -> 8xtz decreasing every 10 minutes.

Charity:
5% of the primary sales will be donated to Ukrainian humanitarian aid funds through the contract set up by @ciphrd and @Veqtor.

Controls:
Key ‚Äôs‚Äô: Save an image of the output at the current resolution (available once the piece has finished generating)
Key ‚ÄòArrow Up‚Äô & ‚ÄòArrow Down‚Äô: Cycle through resolution scaling factors at increments of 1080p. 1080p is the minimum resolution. There is no maximum resolution but loading performance will worsen at higher scaling
Key ‚Äòo‚Äô: Toggle the land outlines on or off

Browser Support:
Confirmed to work on desktop browsers (Chrome Version 99.0.4844.51, Safari v15.3, Firefox v98.0) and Safari iOS v14.8
